11:19.020 --> 11:19.960
Yes, of course.

11:20.080 --> 11:26.240
So, I started working as an interpreter after changing my job.

11:26.380 --> 11:27.680
I used to work at SMART.

11:27.860 --> 11:33.020
Then, I started working as a medical interpreter, mainly for two reasons.

11:33.020 --> 11:38.420
The first one is that, at the beginning, I wanted to be a doctor.

11:38.680 --> 11:41.960
So, I really like all of this stuff.

11:42.940 --> 11:45.920
I feel interested about this.

11:46.480 --> 11:49.740
And the second one is because I love being with people and helping them.

11:49.780 --> 11:51.360
And I think it's a really important job.

11:51.420 --> 11:53.300
It's a job that has a lot of responsibility.

11:53.300 --> 11:56.560
Responsibility is a job that is so important.

11:56.840 --> 12:01.440
I mean, I am really empathetic with the patients.

12:01.940 --> 12:08.480
Like, it would be so difficult to be in a country without speaking the language and not knowing how to explain what you're feeling.

12:08.480 --> 12:11.060
I think that that should be really frustrating.

12:11.620 --> 12:15.100
And I think, wow, I really help people every day.

12:15.440 --> 12:18.620
And right now, I'm working as a medical interpreter with Teleperformance.

12:19.340 --> 12:19.680
Okay.

12:19.860 --> 12:23.060
And a company that is called Language Learning Solutions.

12:23.740 --> 12:24.380
That's a free one.

12:24.400 --> 12:25.780
So, it's like, yes.

12:26.140 --> 12:28.240
It's like Teleperformance hire me.

12:28.800 --> 12:31.800
But I work for this company.

12:32.540 --> 12:32.880
Okay.

12:32.880 --> 12:35.140
So, yes.

12:35.480 --> 12:43.160
So, well, let's say that I have been working with them for about six months.

12:43.700 --> 12:44.040
Okay.

12:44.400 --> 12:47.940
And I want to, you know, see other opportunities.

12:48.580 --> 12:57.880
I want to, well, if I am honest with you, I would like to see what differences can happen.

12:57.880 --> 13:04.600
Because I have had not a really good experience, maybe with the salary and the things they promise.

13:05.340 --> 13:09.740
So, it's like I want to explore what other opportunities I have.

13:10.520 --> 13:19.220
And to, like, stay in a company that what they promise they do.

13:19.780 --> 13:20.120
Okay.

13:20.120 --> 13:20.720
Yeah.

13:20.720 --> 13:25.040
That's why I'm just looking for, maybe for a change.

13:25.280 --> 13:28.980
But it's not because I don't like the job or something like that.

13:29.080 --> 13:30.220
No, it's not that.

13:30.300 --> 13:35.800
It's just I want to know about how other companies operate in this type of business.

13:36.300 --> 13:36.780
Okay.

13:37.320 --> 13:42.200
And besides of your experience at Teleperformance, do you have any other experience as an interpreter?

13:42.480 --> 13:44.100
Or this is, like, the only one?

13:44.900 --> 13:45.980
This is the only one.

13:45.980 --> 13:49.400
Like, the six-month experience I told you, this is the only one.

13:49.400 --> 13:52.280
And also your experience as a teacher.

13:52.520 --> 13:52.840
Okay.

13:53.520 --> 13:54.540
Yes, yes.

13:54.760 --> 13:57.600
I'm a certified English teacher.

13:58.040 --> 13:59.260
I also speak French.

13:59.820 --> 14:00.100
Okay.

14:00.100 --> 14:01.680
And I'm a B2.

14:01.960 --> 14:03.260
In English, I'm a C1.

14:04.080 --> 14:08.820
But, yes, that's pretty much what I can tell you.

14:09.540 --> 14:16.740
Tatiana, some interpreters mentioned to me that it's challenging to be working in that position.

14:16.740 --> 14:27.060
Because, especially, like, in the medical part, because you have to share with the patients so difficult information, no good news all the time.

14:27.060 --> 14:37.020
Sometimes we have to share with them that the drill and the process would be complicated, would be, know what they were expecting.

14:37.940 --> 14:43.520
So, and also sometimes the line could be back to back and all the stuff.

14:43.520 --> 14:53.640
So, but I consider that through the experience, we develop, like, different skills or strategies to be able to handle all those situations.

14:54.140 --> 14:57.760
So, in your case, what would be your strategies or your skills?

14:57.760 --> 15:03.660
For dealing with the common challenges and interpreter phases?

15:04.660 --> 15:05.100
Yeah.

15:06.100 --> 15:06.460
Okay.

15:06.460 --> 15:17.260
I think that before thinking as a interpreter, you have to think as a human.

15:17.860 --> 15:25.220
I think that is a job that requires you to have these customer service skills more than in other positions.

15:25.220 --> 15:29.400
Because it's something that, as you're saying, it's very delicate.

15:30.300 --> 15:39.760
It's a moment where you sometimes, like, might feel that you are not doing enough.

15:39.880 --> 15:47.740
Sometimes it's pretty frustrating because you can say, oh, my God, I would have helped this person more if I had more time.

15:47.740 --> 15:51.600
Or maybe sometimes there are some problems with the platform.

15:51.600 --> 16:00.860
So, maybe the calls hang up on their own and you're like, no, you're feeling like if you didn't do your best.

16:00.980 --> 16:04.440
But I think that you have to be the most human possible.

16:04.920 --> 16:06.860
I think that communication is the key.

16:06.860 --> 16:17.820
So, maybe at these situations where the patients are very angry, because I have had them, of course, that they are very frustrated.

16:18.060 --> 16:21.320
You don't have to say, oh, my God, again, this situation, I'm tired.

16:21.440 --> 16:23.740
But, like, understanding the person.

16:24.000 --> 16:25.960
So, this is the interpreter speaking.

16:26.780 --> 16:34.140
May I, I don't know, ask your client for a clarification or your client is using some profanity.

16:34.140 --> 16:41.720
May I intervene here and say, ma'am, I understand your frustration, but I'm doing my best.

16:41.960 --> 16:48.200
I am the interpreter and I want to translate what you're saying so the other person can understand you.

16:48.300 --> 16:53.520
Could you please calm down for a little bit and let me do my job, ma'am?

16:53.700 --> 16:57.200
So, it's always, like, validating the other people's emotions.

16:57.200 --> 17:11.320
And that key has helped me a lot because, of course, there are calls where they have very difficult things like this migration thing or this kind of insurances calls that people are very mad.

17:11.660 --> 17:20.340
And I try to do my best by, like, being empathetic with the patient and communicating everything to the client.

17:20.340 --> 17:34.680
So, like, being really talkative to the client and that's what helps me a lot.

17:34.840 --> 17:44.160
It's, like, not, like, communicating all I have in my mind, but with respect and with professionalism.

17:44.640 --> 17:46.640
Understanding that my job is very important.

17:46.640 --> 17:48.460
But, yeah, for sure.

17:49.300 --> 17:50.680
That's a very good strategy.

17:50.980 --> 17:54.980
Some people are telling me, like, you cannot have feelings in this job.

17:55.120 --> 17:56.340
And I don't agree with that.

17:56.820 --> 17:57.180
No.

17:57.220 --> 17:57.860
It's impossible.

17:58.880 --> 18:12.640
So, and the last question that I have for you, Tatiana, would be, I know that you mentioned that you want to work in a company that it's, like, following all the promises that they made for you, all the stuff.

18:12.640 --> 18:18.340
